<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-04-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-04-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="132" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d132">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Sir
                                    <persName type="to">Chentung Liang-Cheng</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-04-12"><hi rend="italic">April 12,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Minister</hi>: The President will have
                            great pleasure in receiving His Imperial Highness Prince Pu Lun at the
                            White House on Monday, the 25th, at half past 2. He will also detail
                            Colonel Symons, of the United States Army, to be in attendance upon His
                            Highness during his stay in Washington.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>